"title": "5541: society, negative aspects of",
"media_type": "Text",
"index_reference": "5541",
"language": "eng",
"review_level": "None",
"content": "<p>Often pictured as an immoral city or a world of evil, it is regarded as corrupt and godless, hostile to true faith and therefore destined for judgment.</p>\n<h2>The city as a symbol of corrupt society</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev18:2-Rev18:3\">REV 18:2–18:3</a></strong> <em>Babylon stands for the corrupt Roman state and also for godless society in general.</em> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen11:1-Gen11:9\">GEN 11:1–11:9</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen19:1-Gen19:13\">GEN 19:1–19:13</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek22:1-Ezek22:5\">EZK 22:1–22:5</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt23:37-Matt23:39\">MAT 23:37–23:39</a> parallel <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke13:34-Luke13:35\">LUK 13:34–13:35</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev14:8\">REV 14:8</a></p>\n<h2>``The world'' as a description of society alienated from, and hostile to, both God and his people</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gal3:22\">GAL 3:22</a></strong> <em>The Greek word translated “world” often means not the physical world, but the world of human life.</em> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/John15:18\">JHN 15:18</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Eph6:12\">EPH 6:12</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1John5:19\">1JN 5:19</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev12:9\">REV 12:9</a></p>\n<h2>Fallen society becomes pluralistic</h2>\n<h3>Israel was continually threatened by the pluralism of the surrounding societies</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Josh23:6-Josh23:8\">JOS 23:6–23:8</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod23:32-Exod23:33\">EXO 23:32–23:33</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Josh24:14-Josh24:23\">JOS 24:14–24:23</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Kgs11:1-1Kgs11:6\">1KI 11:1–11:6</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Kgs18:16-1Kgs18:40\">1KI 18:16–18:40</a> <em>Baal was a name used for a variety of local Canaanite deities</em>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezra9:1-Ezra9:2\">EZR 9:1–9:2</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa2:6-Isa2:8\">ISA 2:6–2:8</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Dan3:1-Dan3:12\">DAN 3:1–3:12</a></p>\n<h3>Pluralism was also a feature of the societies of the NT</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts17:16-Acts17:23\">ACT 17:16–17:23</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Cor8:4-1Cor8:6\">1CO 8:4–8:6</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Tim4:3-2Tim4:4\">2TI 4:3–4:4</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1John5:21\">1JN 5:21</a></p>\n<h3>Pluralism is to be resisted and faith in one God and Saviour maintained</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Tim2:5\">1TI 2:5</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa43:10-Isa43:11\">ISA 43:10–43:11</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/John14:6\">JHN 14:6</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts4:12\">ACT 4:12</a></p>\n<h2>Fallen society becomes secular</h2>\n<h3>Life in a godless society becomes spiritually futile and morally depraved</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rom1:21\">ROM 1:21</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rom1:18-Rom1:32\">ROM 1:18–1:32</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Tim3:1-2Tim3:5\">2TI 3:1–3:5</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev18:1-Rev18:3\">REV 18:1–18:3</a></p>\n<h3>Israel ignores warnings about becoming a society which has forgotten God</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps81:11-Ps81:12\">PSA 81:11–81:12</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer3:19-Jer3:21\">JER 3:19–3:21</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Heb3:7-Heb3:11\">HEB 3:7–3:11</a></p>\n<h3>Israel became an example of a society which, though outwardly religious, lived without reference to God</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Amos5:21-Amos5:24\">AMO 5:21–5:24</a></strong> <em>Amos here summarises, and rejects, current religious practices in Israel in the 8th century B.C.</em> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Amos2:6-Amos2:7\">AMO 2:6–2:7</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Amos5:4-Amos5:15\">AMO 5:4–5:15</a> <em>Bethel and Gilgal were popular national shrines, where religion had taken the place of righteousness and relationship</em>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Amos8:4-Amos8:10\">AMO 8:4–8:10</a></p>",
